# Feedback on Your Linked List Implementation

I appreciate you sharing this, but I need to be honest: **this isn't actually a linked list—it's just a wrapper around a JavaScript array.**

## The Core Issue

A linked list should use **nodes with pointers/references** to each other, not an underlying array. Your implementation defeats the purpose of using a linked list.

## What's Wrong

1. **Not a true linked list**: Uses `this.data = []` internally, so you get array performance characteristics, not linked list ones
2. **Misleading API**: Users expect linked list performance (O(1) insertions/deletions at known positions), but get array performance instead
3. **Missing node structure**: No `Node` class with `value` and `next` properties

## A Proper Linked List Implementation

```javascript
class Node {
    constructor(value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.next = null;
    }
}

class LinkedList {
    constructor() {
        this.head = null;
        this.tail = null;
        this.size = 0;
    }

    add(value) {
        const node = new Node(value);
        if (!this.head) {
            this.head = node;
            this.tail = node;
        } else {
            this.tail.next = node;
            this.tail = node;
        }
        this.size++;
    }

    remove(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;

        let current = this.head;
        if (index === 0) {
            this.head = current.next;
        } else {
            let prev;
            for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) {
                prev = current;
                current = current.next;
            }
            prev.next = current.next;
            if (index === this.size - 1) this.tail = prev;
        }
        this.size--;
        return current.value;
    }

    get(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;

        let current = this.head;
        for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) {
            current = current.next;
        }
        return current.value;
    }
}
```

## When to Use What

- **Use an array** if you need random access and don't care about insertion/deletion costs
- **Use a linked list** if you need efficient insertions/deletions at known positions
- **If you just need a list**, JavaScript's built-in array is usually the right choice

What's your use case? That might help determine the best data structure.
